# Kasagadi AI — System Manual

A working reference for how the Kasagadi AI fact-checking platform is built and how it
behaves. Useful to a new engineer joining the team, a product person needing to reason
about the lifecycle of a claim, or a designer wanting to know which states each screen
represents.

---

## 1. What the platform does

Kasagadi AI is a Ghana-focused fact-checking marketplace. Members of the public submit
claims they want investigated. Admins triage those claims and assign them to accredited
fact checkers. Fact checkers research the claim, write a verdict, and submit it back.
Admins approve the verdict for publication, at which point the claim becomes visible on
the public marketplace.

The platform is built so that the journey from "I saw a suspicious headline" to "here is
a verified verdict with evidence and a research trail" lives in one auditable system.

---

## 2. The actors

There are three roles. A `User` record holds the credentials and shared profile
(name, email, avatar). A user becomes one of three roles by being associated with a
`Member`, `FactChecker`, or `Admin` profile record. The role helpers
(`user.member?`, `user.fact_checker?`, `user.admin?`) drive routing and authorization.

| Role          | How they get one                              | What they can do                                                                 |
|---------------|------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Member        | Self-signs up at `/registration/new`           | Submit claims, save drafts, edit/destroy own drafts, browse the marketplace      |
| Fact checker  | Invited by an admin (`/admins/invitations`)    | View their assignments, accept/reject them, submit verdicts                      |
| Admin         | Provisioned manually (no public sign-up)       | Triage claims, assign checkers, approve/archive, invite fact checkers            |

Public visitors (no account) can browse the marketplace and read published claims.

